{"type":"message","id":"ff103ad9","parentId":"08cd7eef","timestamp":"2026-03-27T03:51:28.900Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the key insight:\n\n1. **`runtime_risk_state_latest.json`** is written by **`generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py`** (line 356) as the authoritative runtime state. It's the \"runtime truth source\".\n\n2. **`today_stock_strategy_report_{date}.json`** is the output of the same script, which reads from runtime_risk_state and generates a strategy report.\n\n3. **`event_watch`** is from the investment research system.\n\nThe inconsistency stems from:\n- `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` generated at 11:00:18 (mode=normal)\n- `today_stock_strategy_report_20260327.json` generated at 11:35:11 (risk_mode=halt, halt_new_buy=True)\n\n\n- These are actually different fields: runtime_risk_state.mode vs today_stock_strategy_report.risk_mode\n\nThe core issue is that runtime_risk_state_latest.json holds the authoritative runtime state (normal at 11:00), but today_stock_strategy_report_20260327.json appears to compute or override risk_mode independently at a later timestamp, creating the halt vs normal contradiction.\n\nNow I need to check generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py to see where halt_new_buy actually gets determined, and also look at the event_watch file to trace its source.","thinkingSignature":"1c715a28baadcc32b52c1f65c3d01d39d10fdb6a94ee9b3fe89d7f146af46e98"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_lr1nmbg9nq69_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport json\nd=json.load(open('research/reports/investment_research_event_watch_20260327.json'))\npe = ((d.get('current') or {}).get('paper_execution_status') or {})\nprint('generated_at:', d.get('generated_at'))\nprint('paper_execution_status source:', pe.get('source'))\nprint('mode:', pe.get('mode'))\nprint('halt_new_buy:', pe.get('halt_new_buy'))\n\" 2>/dev/null","workdir":"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace"}}],"api":"anthr