{"type":"message","id":"9be83484","parentId":"cc4bca9f","timestamp":"2026-03-27T03:52:04.089Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `auto_run_premarket_precheck.py` doesn't write to `runtime_risk_state_latest.json`. This file is only written by `generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py`.\n\nThe P1-001 issue is:\n1. `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` (written by generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py at 11:00) has mode=normal, halt_new_buy=False\n2. When `generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py` runs again at 11:35, it:\n   - Reads runtime_risk_state_latest.json (still the 11:00 version: normal)\n   - Computes halt from paper_profiles (some are halt, hence halt=True in the report)\n   - Writes the strategy report with halt=True\n   - BUT it doesn't update runtime_risk_state_latest.json!\n\nThe `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` only gets updated by `generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py` at line 356, but I need to trace through the full function logic around lines 400-435 to see if it's actually being written to with the fresh halt value or if there's a gap where the runtime state isn't being refreshed with the computed halt decision.\n\nLooking at the code structure, there's conditional logic at lines 404 and 420-432 that determines what gets written, and if the if-block at line 404 isn't being triggered, the runtime state might not be updated at all.\n\nThe real problem seems to be that runtime_risk_state_latest.json is only written during the first execution, so when the script runs again later and computes different halt values from the paper profiles, those new values get written to the strategy report but don't update the runtime state file itself. I need to find where runtime_risk_state_latest.json is actually being written to confirm this theory.","thinkingSignature":"7cd0fd3b28642dd4f6c42a355681206e09a5b71b693e4b24df3ba684ede76b05"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_p2hpugqek3el_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command