{"type":"message","id":"2c7ce007","parentId":"cba62dfd","timestamp":"2026-03-27T03:55:02.306Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"`QUANT_REPORT_DIR` points to `quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/research/reports/`, and `REPORT_DIR` points to `research/reports/`. So:\n\n- `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` is at `QUANT_REPORT_DIR / \"runtime_risk_state_latest.json\"` = `quant_projects/.../reports/runtime_risk_state_latest.json`\n- `today_stock_strategy_report_*.json` is also in `QUANT_REPORT_DIR`\n- `event_watch_*.json` is in `REPORT_DIR` (workspace research/reports)\n\n\n- `apply_runtime_overlay` pulls from `QUANT_REPORT_DIR` for both the runtime object and report path, which are the same directories the strategy report itself uses.\n\nThe P1-001 issue stems from the event_watch fallback incorrectly using strategy_report values when it shouldn't. The cleanest solution is to have generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py update `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` immediately after computing `halt_new_buy`, so the runtime state file stays current and the fallback never triggers unnecessarily.\n\nI need to verify that `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` uses a `latest_runtime` sub-object structure, then implement the fix in the strategy report generation script.","thinkingSignature":"fb9b5e33ec5194cb5c8221f1254fa197a990d3c6cb917d1e1bc3a5e7b7b7a0fe"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_iu43esewbc4q_1","name":"read","arguments":{"offset":520,"limit":30,"file_path":"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":47768,"output":341,"cacheRead":23032,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":71141,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774583693359,"responseId":"0615328dbb6be47fa90024bdcd7eeaee"}}
