{"type":"message","id":"16fc1b33","parentId":"793beff4","timestamp":"2026-03-27T03:56:34.736Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The findings are still there because:\n1. The fix requires a fresh run of `generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py` to update `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` with the new halt value.\n2. The current `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` still has the old values.\n\nLet me re-run `generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py` to trigger the fix. Actually, looking at the issue more carefully:\n\nThe problem is that the `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` is ONLY updated when `generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py` is run AND when it computes `risk_mode`/`halt_new_buy`. But this file hasn't been updated since 11:00 because the strategy report already ran at 11:35.\n \nMy fix is correct—it writes the computed halt values back to `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` after the strategy report computes them. But the issue is that the strategy report runs after `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` is loaded, so the file is read at 11:35 with the old halt values already in memory. When the report computes its own halt values from paper_profiles and attempts to write them back, there might be a timing or conditional issue preventing the update.\n\nLooking at the code path, `risk_mode` gets computed from `resolve_risk_mode(profile_stats)` regardless of whether `runtime_snapshot.authoritative` is True or False. In both branches, the strategy report ends up with `risk_mode=halt` and `halt_new_buy=True` from the profile_stats, but this never actually updates the runtime state file. My fix would write these computed values back to `runtime_risk_state_latest.json`, which would then be picked up by the next event watch run. The audit is still showing the old values because the strategy report hasn't been re-run since I applied the fix.\n\nI should re-run the strategy report to verify the fix actually works, though I'm wondering if this should be automated. The P1-001 rule might need to be adjusted so that the strategy report doesn't even attempt to compute `risk_mode` if `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` already has an authoritative `latest_runtime` section with a recent `generated_at`.\n\nActually, re-reading the audit findings, `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` has `mode=normal` from 11:00, so it does have a `latest_runtime` section. The real issue is that the strategy report ignores this and computes its own `risk_mode=halt` from `paper_profiles`, then writes that back to `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` instead of preserving the original value.\n\nMy fix should resolve this, but I should test it by running the strategy report to see if the runtime state actually updates correctly.","thinkingSignature":"375d1a5d8fecf417af61839809e29af49758f5d38bdb1a32158f3e57a3a6fb82"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_54s9sb1t3tmu_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace && python3 quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/scripts/generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py --date 2026-03-27 2>&1 | tail -5","yieldMs":55000,"timeout":60}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":52841,"output":664,"cacheRead":23032,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":76537,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774583778630,"responseId":"061532e2e3ce6e4686bfd31fdcac73ad"}}
