{"type":"message","id":"4fd1d006","parentId":"65d2b6c8","timestamp":"2026-03-27T03:58:03.561Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Hmm, event_watch is still showing `source=paper_profiles, mode=halt, halt_new_buy=True`. But `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` was updated at 11:56:34 to `mode=cautious, halt_new_buy=False`. So event_watch should have read from `runtime_risk_state_latest` (since date_tag matches) and used those values.\n\nLet me re-read the event_watch logic to understand why it's still using paper_profiles.Looking at `apply_runtime_overlay` again:\n- Line 80: `if str(runtime_obj.get(\"date_tag\") or \"\") == date_tag and latest_runtime:`\n  - Sets `source=runtime_risk_state_latest`\n- Else fallback:\n  - `source=paper_profiles`\n\nSo if the condition is TRUE, source should be `runtime_risk_state_latest`. But the current event_watch shows `source=paper_profiles`. This means the condition was FALSE.\n\nThe condition checks whether `runtime_obj.get(\"date_tag\")` matches today's date and whether `latest_runtime` exists. My runtime_risk_state_latest.json has `date_tag=20260327` and `latest_runtime` is populated, so the condition should be true. Yet the event_watch is falling back to `paper_profiles`, which suggests either the date_tag comparison is failing or the latest_runtime object is somehow empty when the script runs.\n\nLet me trace through the `apply_runtime_overlay` function more carefully. It loads both `runtime_obj` and `report_obj` from their respective files, then extracts `latest_runtime` from `runtime_obj`. The issue might be that when `apply_runtime_overlay` is called, the `runtime_obj` being passed in doesn't have the expected structure or date_tag value, even though the file itself appears correct.\n\nLooking at how the overlay logic works, it updates the `paper_execution_status` dict with values from `latest_runtime` if the date_tag matches. But then there's a second fallback block that checks if the trade date matches and uses the strategy report values instead — and this fallback uses `setdefault`, which means it only sets values if they're not already present. So if the first block already populated those fields from `latest_runtime`, the fallback shouldn't override them. Unless the condition for the first block isn't being met, which would explain why we're seeing `source=paper_profiles` in the output despite `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` having a valid `date_tag`.\n\nThe `generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py` script runs with today's date (2026-03-27), so `date_tag` should be set to `20260327`. But the runtime_risk_state file might have been written with a different date_tag, or the `latest_runtime` section might be missing when the script reads it. Let me trace through what `generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py` actually does when it loads and updates that JSON file. The condition checks if the runtime state's date_tag matches today's date and has a latest_runtime entry, which should be true since we just wrote those values. But I'm realizing my sync code only updates `latest_runtime` fields—it doesn't preserve the original `mode` value if it wasn't already set. Looking at my code, I see I'm setting `mode`, `halt_new_buy`, and other fields in `latest_runtime`, but if the original file had `mode=normal` and my code didn't explicitly overwrite it, the old value might persist depending on how the update is structured.\n\nActually, wait—the runtime_risk_state_latest.json shows `mode=cautious` and `halt_new_buy=False` now, so those values were definitely updated. Yet the event_watch is still reading `source=paper_profiles` and `mode=halt` from 11:57, which is after my update at 11:56:34. Something's off with how the event_watch is reading the runtime state, or maybe my JSON structure doesn't match what the event_watch expects.\n\nLooking at the apply_runtime_overlay logic more carefully—the condition checking `date_tag` and `latest_runtime` should pass since both match, but the fallback is still kicking in. Let me trace through what's actually happening in the event_watch code to see where the mismatch is occurring. Looking at the fallback condition more carefully — it's checking if `trade_date_text` matches `date_tag`, if `report_obj` exists, and most crucially, if `latest_runtime` is falsy. That last condition is key: when `latest_runtime` is an empty dict it's falsy, so the entire fallback block executes and overwrites the PE dict that was just set in the runtime overlay block.\n\nThe real issue is that `latest_runtime` from the runtime_obj is empty, even though `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` contains `latest_runtime` data. I need to verify whether `load_runtime_overlay` is actually returning the runtime_obj with the `latest_runtime` field populated when loading from that file.","thinkingSignature":"071b93c61e97cfe023dc0950e4d2345ee7b119a7bc1b221b74f9383c1d2cdc11"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ekpnlu9jmvfp_1","name":"read","arguments":{"offset":48,"limit":50,"file_path":"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/scripts/run_investment_research_event_watch.py"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":55982,"output":1104,"cacheRead":23032,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":80118,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774583855129,"responseId":"0615332fffcfee4523c11843bc171399"}}
{"type":"message","id":"4c9727f2","parentId":"4fd1d006","timestamp":"2026-03-27T03:58:03.668Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ekpnlu9jmvfp_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"        except ValueError:\n            continue\n    return datetime.min\n\n\ndef load_runtime_overlay(date_tag: str) -> tuple[dict[str, Any], dict[str, Any]]:\n    runtime_obj: dict[str, Any] = {}\n    report_obj: dict[str, Any] = {}\n    if RUNTIME_STATE_LATEST.exists():\n        try:\n            runtime_obj = load_json(RUNTIME_STATE_LATEST)\n        except Exception:\n            runtime_obj = {}\n    report_path = QUANT_REPORT_DIR / f\"today_stock_strategy_report_{date_tag}.json\"\n    if not report_path.exists():\n        report_path = QUANT_REPORT_DIR / \"today_stock_strategy_report_latest.json\"\n    if report_path.exists():\n        try:\n            report_obj = load_json(report_path)\n        except Exception:\n            report_obj = {}\n    return runtime_obj, report_obj\n\n\ndef apply_runtime_overlay(summary: dict[str, Any]) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    date_tag = str(summary.get(\"strategy_report_date_tag\") or summary.get(\"paper_date_tag\") or datetime.now().strftime(\"%Y%m%d\"))\n    runtime_obj, report_obj = load_runtime_overlay(date_tag)\n    latest_runtime = runtime_obj.get(\"latest_runtime\") or {}\n\n    if str(runtime_obj.get(\"date_tag\") or \"\") == date_tag and latest_runtime:\n        summary[\"risk_off\"] = bool(latest_runtime.get(\"risk_off\"))\n        pe = dict(summary.get(\"paper_execution_status\") or {})\n        pe.update(\n            {\n                \"source\": \"runtime_risk_state_latest\",\n                \"mode\": latest_runtime.get(\"mode\"),\n                \"risk_off\": latest_runtime.get(\"risk_off\"),\n                \"hard_stop\": latest_runtime.get(\"hard_stop\"),\n                \"halt_new_buy\": latest_runtime.get(\"halt_new_buy\"),\n                \"halt_reason\": latest_runtime.get(\"halt_reason\"),\n                \"market_breadth\": latest_runtime.get(\"market_breadth\"),\n                \"gate_reasons\": latest_runtime.get(\"gate_reasons\") or [],\n                \"allowed_to_open_new_positions\": not bool(latest_runtime.get(\"halt_new_buy\")),\n                \"runtime_state_path\": str(RUNTIME_STATE_LATEST),\n            }\n        )\n        summary[\"paper_execution_status\"] = pe\n        source_paths = dict(summary.get(\"source_paths\") or {})\n        source_paths[\"runtime_risk_state_json\"] = str(RUNTIME_STATE_LATEST)\n        summary[\"source_paths\"] = source_paths\n\n[203 more lines in file. Use offset=98 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774583883657}}
