{"type":"message","id":"a2a0731f","parentId":"e1bf7b33","timestamp":"2026-03-27T04:01:32.045Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so `summary[\"paper_execution_status\"]` is obtained from `org.make_summary(snapshot, datetime.now())`. The `org` module is the `investment_research` package. Let me find it.\n\nActually, I now understand the P1-001 issue much better. The `event_watch` is getting its data from an organization module (`org`) that builds the summary. The `apply_runtime_overlay` then tries to overlay runtime data on top, but if the base `paper_execution_status` from `org` has stale data (from yesterday), and the `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` condition fails, then the event_watch keeps the stale data.\n \nLooking at the `apply_runtime_overlay` function, it's checking whether to pull from `runtime_risk_state_latest` or fall back to `strategy_report`, but the real problem is that `summary[\"paper_execution_status\"]` coming from the organization layer is already stale from yesterday. The `source_date_tag` in the event_watch output is `20260326` instead of today's `20260327`, which suggests the org module isn't refreshing properly. When `apply_runtime_overlay` gets called with this stale summary and tries to apply overlays, the overlay logic itself is sound, but it's working with bad base data.\n\nThe core P1-001 issue is that three different components—`runtime_risk_state_latest.json`, the strategy report, and event_watch—are using different sources and staying out of sync. My fix addresses part of this by ensuring the strategy report updates `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` when it computes halt, and my test confirmed the condition checking `date_tag` and `latest_runtime` does pass, so the overlay should theoretically work. But the stale data from the org layer is still contaminating the whole flow.\n\nThe real problem is that the `event_watch` output shows `source_date_tag=20260326`, meaning the paper_execution_status is pulling yesterday's data from the organization module, not from the runtime overlay. So even though the overlay logic is correct, it's operating on stale base data. What I really need to do is ensure the organization module itself gets refreshed with today's information before the overlay runs. The event_watch has `source_date_tag: 20260326`, which suggests it's pulling stale data from somewhere in the investment research system. Rather than chase down where this date originates, I should focus on fixing P1-001 itself: my strategy report fix now syncs computed halt state back to `runtime_risk_state_latest.json`, and the audit script validates that when `event_watch` uses the latest runtime file, the `mode` and `halt_new_buy` values are consistent. The remaining stale `source_date_tag` issue is a separate concern to investigate later.\n\nTo fully resolve P1-001, I need to ensure that when the strategy report runs, it not only updates `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` but the event watch also picks up that updated runtime state on the next run. My fix addresses the first part, but the second part depends on whether `apply_runtime_overlay` correctly references `runtime_risk_state_latest` as the authoritative source.\n\nLooking at the root cause: `runtime_risk_state_latest.json` had `mode=normal` from the morning run, the strategy report computed `halt=True` from afternoon profiles but didn't persist this back to the runtime state file, and the event watch fell back to `paper_profiles` since the runtime state didn't reflect the computed halt. My fix ensures the strategy report writes the computed halt back to `runtime_risk_state_latest.json`, so when the event watch reads it next time, it gets the correct state.\n\nThe remaining findings show that event_watch still has `source_date_tag=20260326` with `mode=halt`, which appears to be stale data from the organization summary itself, not a fresh computation. The runtime state file was last updated at 11:56 with `mode=cautious` and `halt_new_buy=False`, so the event_watch should be reading from there instead of carrying forward yesterday's halt mode.\n\nLooking at the actual overlay logic, I'm realizing the issue might be in how the source attribution works. When the strategy report computes halt, it writes to `runtime_risk_state_latest.json`, but then when the event_watch applies the overlay, it's incorrectly attributing the halt to `paper_profiles` as the source instead of recognizing it came from the strategy report's computation.\n\nThe real problem seems to be that the `make_summary` function in the organization module is pulling stale data with `paper_date_tag=20260326` from somewhere, which then overwrites what should be the fresh halt state. I need to trace where this old date_tag is coming from in the summary construction. I see the fallback block only runs when the runtime object lacks fresh data, but the runtime check actually passes since date_tag matches and latest_runtime exists. So the fallback shouldn't execute at all. Let me trace through the event_watch script itself to figure out what's actually happening with the overlay logic.\n\nActually, I should just directly modify the event_watch script to fix the date_tag comparison—if it's using the old `20260326` instead of today's `20260327`, that would explain why the runtime overlay isn't being applied when it should be.","thinkingSignature":"1c27fdee4dddce1d21ce29aa4be6ace72c3cd46aeffed28dc38f146692797baf"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qahm9j2yj6bc_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"date_tag\\|paper_date_tag\\|strategy_report\" scripts/run_investment_research_event_watch.py | grep -v \"^[0-9]*:.*#\" | head -20","workdir":"/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":65256,"output":1196,"cacheRead":23032,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":89484,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0