{"type":"message","id":"fb9aa3fc","parentId":"4c1cc16f","timestamp":"2026-03-27T10:18:07.720Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The tester reads `today_stock_strategy_report_{date_tag}.json` first, and only falls back to `today_stock_strategy_report_latest.json` if the dated file is empty/missing. Since the dated file exists and is non-empty (just stale), the tester reads the stale dated file.\n\nThe `generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py` script is what writes the dated file. It was run this morning (producing the dated file with `normal/False`). The close bundle at 15:20 didn't re-run it, so the dated file stayed stale.\n\nThis is a systemic issue: the close bundle doesn't re-run `generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py`, so the dated file becomes stale after the morning run. \n\nI could fix this by having the close bundle re-run `generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py`, or I could modify the tester to always prefer the latest file when its `generated_at` timestamp is more recent than the dated version. The real problem is that both files need to stay synchronized, but they're being written at different times by different processes.\n\nThe cleanest solution is to have `generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py` write to the dated path during the close bundle run, while keeping the morning run's dated output separate. This way the dated file reflects the most current state after market close, and I can fix the tester to use the `generated_at` timestamps to determine which file is actually more recent rather than relying on file naming conventions.","thinkingSignature":"ca30b186f06fa86e31b12f07123fd6164c16e4df6ada08a094af0f3d685ac414"},{"type":"text","text":"The tester reads a stale dated file while `today_stock_strategy_report_latest.json` (updated 15:20) has the correct `halt=True`. Let me fix the tester to always prefer the more recent file:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_9yttjxofpvkn_1","name":"read","arguments