{"type":"message","id":"f8fd38c2","parentId":"2822ea1b","timestamp":"2026-03-27T10:18:27.294Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, but the current logic is: dated is from 11:35 (generated_at), latest is from 15:20. The dated file is more recent in terms of generated_at. But the LATEST file has the MORE RELEVANT/CURRENT data (halt=True). The dated file has OLD data (halt=False).\n\nActually I had the comparison backwards in my proposed fix. Let me reconsider.\n\nThe `today_stock_strategy_report_latest.json` was updated at 15:20 with `halt=True`. The `today_stock_strategy_report_20260327.json` (dated) was from 11:35 with `halt=False`. \n\n\nThe dated file's `generated_at` of 11:35 is actually earlier than the latest file's 15:20, so `latest_ts > dated_ts` and the comparison would correctly pick the latest file anyway. But actually, I need to reconsider what this is really solving—the tester is using the runtime's halt status (which comes from the latest file at 15:20 showing halt=True) to compare against the report's status.\n\nThe report it's reading from the dated file at 11:35 shows halt=False, creating a mismatch. The solution is to have the tester read whichever file has the more recent `generated_at` timestamp. The `generate_today_stock_strategy_report.py` script updates both files when it runs, so they'd have matching timestamps when updated together. But the close bundle at 15:20 only updates the latest file, leaving the dated file stale—that's the root cause of this inconsistency.\n\nThe immediate fix is to ensure the tester reads from the most recent file based on `generated_at`, and the deeper solution is to have the close bundle regenerate the dated file so both stay in sync going forward.","thinkingSignature":"6b4ac2523ce50b24d13a6f4d5d1336c080eb8b2fdbaf44372a945aaba086cd0b"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_m32ja8bkrdh6_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -m py_compile scripts/run_tester_schedu